</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F51A14F50A1148C6E84F63D348440C1B" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
Syn.: 
<taxonomicName id="F7BBB20481E998CB49E1F8452A968ED3" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Marasmius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Marasmius brevipes" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="brevipes">Marasmius brevipes</taxonomicName>
Berk. &amp; Ravenel, in Berkeley and Curtis, Ann. Mag. Nat. Hist., Ser. 2 12: 426. 1853.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="227259325D541EF1416ACD300D75641D" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
= 
<taxonomicName id="9E57BCF0F9989AB0864F3ED30404EC2F" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Micromphale" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Micromphale brevipes" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="brevipes">Micromphale brevipes</taxonomicName>
(Berk. &amp; Ravenel) Singer, in Dennis, Kew Bull. 8: 42. 1953.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B33A15B4AF64833C6E4C99BA7B76FD7C" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
Not 
<taxonomicName id="273F9899D5F2363BC6777B8CF0A77066" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Agaricaceae" genus="Agaricus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Agaricus brevipes" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="brevipes">Agaricus brevipes</taxonomicName>
Bull., Herb. Fr. 11: tab. 521. 1791 (
<taxonomicName id="A020DC731A36F5DE1AF2EED445BD4F8E" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Gymnopus</taxonomicName>
, Gray, Nat. Arr. Brit. Pl. 1: 609.1821; 
<taxonomicName id="390E111046F1FE8005C4EB012E803E37" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Tricholomataceae" genus="Melanoleuca" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Melanoleuca" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Melanoleuca</taxonomicName>
, Pat., Essai Tax. 
<normalizedToken id="A38B47EB55B32FA7F8027BA9EF1993B1" originalValue="Hyménomyc">Hymenomyc</normalizedToken>
.: 158, 1900.).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="A4ADA70646EF751D401AF9A5EF56CA62" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
Reports of marasmioid fungi as nesting material for 
<taxonomicName id="3CF91B9CE8F547138B03B1F3C1A8EF05" genus="Rhizomorphigena" lsidName="Rhizomorphigena" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="order">Passeriformes</taxonomicName>
have been referred in several works as filaments, rhizomorphs or horse-hair fungi and recorded from the Nearctic and the Neotropical regions (
<bibRefCitation id="2954F210E647098ED39525D426A7A59F" author="Sick, H" journalOrPublisher="Journal fuer Ornithologie" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="421 - 431" title="Rosthaarpilze als Nestbau-Material Brasilianischer Vogel." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF01671688" volume="98" year="1957">Sick 1957</bibRefCitation>
; Mc Farland and Rimmer 1996; 
<bibRefCitation id="DA8203DD7D203E8CE685845882227FFC" author="Aubrecht, G" journalOrPublisher="Avian Biology research" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="26 - 30" title="Coincidence or benefit? The use of Marasmius (horse-hair fungus) filaments in bird nests." url="https://doi.org/10.3184/175815512X13531739538638" volume="6" year="2013">Aubrecht et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
). These fungal materials have been identified as 
<taxonomicName id="D0B8393B597DA4F53E183BC73AD25810" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Marasmius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Marasmius androsaceus" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="androsaceus">Marasmius androsaceus</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="949C8382F207D0502A31CB5A86190D99" genus="M." lsidName="M. brevipes" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="brevipes">M. brevipes</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="E7072C06FC014FB7A9BA2F85B0A8A9C1" genus="M." lsidName="M. crinis-equi" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="crinis-equi">M. crinis-equi</taxonomicName>
F. Muell. ex Kalchbr., 
<taxonomicName id="185DBB4E3550E9B6CF72538849ADE7F1" genus="M." lsidName="M. nigrobrunneus" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="nigrobrunneus">M. nigrobrunneus</taxonomicName>
(Pat.) Sacc. and 
<taxonomicName id="065C3C0B1BB30449D234FDC3E98EF005" genus="M." lsidName="M." pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="genus">M.</taxonomicName>
sp. Fungal material from 
<taxonomicName id="64A74D2647E2AB7BB96EFE755B3B6658" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Marasmius" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Marasmius" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Marasmius</taxonomicName>
sp. and 
<taxonomicName id="F975EFA59ECF16C4EA23F0E34D513D81" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Marasmiaceae" genus="Crinipellis" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Crinipellis" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Crinipellis</taxonomicName>
sp. was recorded in Mexico as being associated with nests of birds in a tropical forest from Tabasco in the south of Mexico (
<bibRefCitation id="81DC0D62495CCB0566840722B42D0E69" author="Gomez, VH" journalOrPublisher="Ornitologia Neotropical" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="107 - 111" title="Nidos de aves elaborados con material fungico: un dato no registrado en Mexico." volume="25" year="2014">
<normalizedToken id="37C5BB51C0A9400E344D44A93708B46C" originalValue="Gómez">Gomez</normalizedToken>
et al. 2014
</bibRefCitation>
). In the present study, one of the sequences (MH560578), included in the obtained phylogeny (Fig. 1), belongs to a rhizomorph of 
<taxonomicName id="F07D58D3364FDF13E57A4036F3C10B6C" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus nidus-avis" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="species" species="nidus-avis">Gymnopus nidus-avis</taxonomicName>
re-collected in a nest of 
<taxonomicName id="FC6D58602BC6915460A882B4028CA7B6" authority="Staude, 1854" authorityName="Staude" authorityYear="1854" class="Aves" family="Tyrannidae" genus="Myonectes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myonectes oleaginous" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oleaginous">Myonectes oleaginous</taxonomicName>
Lichtenstein. This 
<taxonomicName id="154B2CA47477B4F0A31A7C7F66381F71" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Gymnopus</taxonomicName>
species represents a new species in the list of marasmioid taxa found interacting with birds.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7EA80F57F84AC337F3FFC7ED95B51CE3" pageId="0" pageNumber="21">
All the basidiomes collected in the present study were found on fallen twigs in the low canopy level but it is possible that fructifications occur also on rhizomorphs at the top of the trees, where these latter are found and used by birds. Previous reports have suggested that bird efforts of picking this inconspicuous material is rewarded with the high tensile strength, reduced water uptake and antimicrobial properties of the rhizomorphs, which consequently protect the offspring (
<bibRefCitation id="F43A30A558070E9526B353028BB38F94" author="Aubrecht, G" journalOrPublisher="Avian Biology research" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="26 - 30" title="Coincidence or benefit? The use of Marasmius (horse-hair fungus) filaments in bird nests." url="https://doi.org/10.3184/175815512X13531739538638" volume="6" year="2013">Aubrecht et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="A65026A157F632F326297D74BE00EA8D" author="Freymann, BP" journalOrPublisher="Ibis" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="395 - 399" title="Physical properties of fungal rhizomorphs of marasmioid basidiomicetes used as nesting material by birds." url="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1474-919X.2007.00750.x" volume="150" year="2007">Freymann 2007</bibRefCitation>
). Preliminary results, based on various sequences obtained from rhizomorphs gathered in different nests of bird species found in the study site, suggest the presence of an important diversity of marasmioid rhizomorph-forming species in the cloud forest studied. It is interesting to note also that we could evidence the presence of nests of wasps of 
<taxonomicName id="D526015A8B5DFDB548743F88EB1B4C9B" class="Insecta" family="Eumenidae" genus="Polybia" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Polybia rejecta" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rejecta">Polybia rejecta</taxonomicName>
Fabricius, near one of 
<taxonomicName id="6BFE6D94D43D42DA51CD767895DB759E" authority="Staude, 1854" authorityName="Staude" authorityYear="1854" class="Aves" family="Tyrannidae" genus="Myonectes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Myonectes oleagineus" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="oleagineus">Myonectes oleagineus</taxonomicName>
built with rhizomorphs of 
<taxonomicName id="45390600945F981BF3EC3FB60340C419" class="Agaricomycetes" family="Omphalotaceae" genus="Gymnopus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Gymnopus" order="Agaricales" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Basidiomycota" rank="genus">Gymnopus</taxonomicName>
. It coincides with the observations made by 
<bibRefCitation id="4A35546EB42A9CFFCCF0F368A9BE6E41" author="Joyce, FJ" journalOrPublisher="Behavioral Ecology and Sociobiology" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" pagination="71 - 77" title="Nesting success of rufous-naped wrens is greater near wasp nests." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/BF00164038" volume="32" year="1993">Joyce (1993)</bibRefCitation>
in Costa Rica regarding the presence of nests of that wasp species near 
<taxonomicName id="BDAA582D221851FC8E681BA9BDE0E90E" genus="Tolmomyas" lsidName="Tolmomyas sulphurescens" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" rank="species" species="sulphurescens">Tolmomyas sulphurescens</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="24E434374946CD90A9498D0B30E8F291" class="Aves" family="Icteridae" genus="Cacicus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Cacicus" order="Passeriformes" pageId="0" pageNumber="21" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Cacicus</taxonomicName>
spp. nests. These latter authors concluded that such association could reduce predation, remarking the importance of the fungal rhizomorphs in this complex ecological interaction.
</paragraph>
